<Base
  title="Causal Inferential Yield · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="A graded, falsifiable measure of how much of the licensing structure a model actually uses — built so it cannot quietly collapse back into accuracy."
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Paper 3 · quantitative grading
    </div>
    <h1>Causal Inferential Yield</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      How much causal structure does the model reliably extract?
    </p>

    <p>
      Causal Inferential Yield (CIY) asks not merely whether the licensing structure is used, or
      where it is used, but how much causal structure the model reliably extracts. It is Paper 3 in
      the core sequence: <a href="/research/sc-certification">Stable Is Not Grounded</a> gives
      binary certification, <a href="/research/isotrace">Isotrace</a> gives path localization, and
      CIY aims at quantitative grading.
    </p>

    <CIYFigure />

    <h2>Measurement domain</h2>
    <p>
      CIY should be defined on items whose grounding status is already certified or controlled, not
      on arbitrary benchmark accuracy. Otherwise the measure risks grading whatever signal happens
      to correlate with the answer, rather than the causal structure that should license it.
    </p>

    <p>
      In the cleanest case, the item graph is stipulated and the relevant interventions are
      auditable. In the sandbox case, the generating structure is planted. Those are the regimes in
      which a yield measure has a target to be wrong about.
    </p>

    <h2>Falsifiability criterion</h2>
    <p>
      The design constraint is falsifiability. If CIY cannot distinguish accuracy-matched and
      grounding-matched models, then it collapses into a repackaging of accuracy and should not be
      treated as a new measure. The instantiation protocol is designed to expose that collapse, not
      paper over it.
    </p>

    <h2>Role in the program</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Paper 1:</strong> binary certification — is the licensing structure load-bearing?</li>
      <li><strong>Paper 2:</strong> path localization — which hop was used, bypassed, or shortcut-replaced?</li>
      <li><strong>Paper 3:</strong> quantitative grading — how much of the certified or controlled structure is reliably extracted?</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Mini Causal Models are the supporting sandbox for this step: because the ground-truth graph is
      planted, CIY-style grading can be tested against a known target before being applied to less
      controlled settings.
    </p>

    <hr/>
    <p class="!text-sm !text-[var(--color-text-muted)]">An interactive falsifiability widget will live here.</p>
  </article>
</Base>
